# Pokémon Battle Agent-based Model: Evolution of Cooperation

**ENGG*3130 Modelling Complex Systems - Final Project Demo**  

This notebook demonstrates our agent-based model of Pokémon battles as our way of studying the *evolution of cooperation*. Trainers with different battle strategies compete in an Axelrod-style tournament. Over multiple generations, natural selection shapes which strategies dominate the population.

The model connects directly to Chapter 12 of *Think Complexity* (Downey): instead of a Prisoner's Dilemma payoff matrix, fitness is determined by high-fidelity Pokémon battle mechanics - type effectiveness, status conditions, stat boosts, and more.

---
**Strategies modelled:**
| Strategy | Description | PD Analogue |
|---|---|---|
| `random` | Picks any legal action at random | Random |
| `greedy` | Always uses the highest expected-damage move | Always Defect |
| `minimax` | One-ply lookahead over all action pairs | Tit-for-Tat |
| `stall` | Maximises attrition via recovery/poison | Always Cooperate (passive) |
| `setup_sweep` | Sets up stat boosts when safe, then bursts | Tit-for-Tat (patient) |
